data.content:
Here's a complete migration analysis and rewrite:

## Problem Inventory

| API | Location | Pattern | Issue on .NET 8 |
|-----|----------|---------|-----------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption | `SYSLIB0046` — obsolete in .NET 9, unreliable in .NET 8 |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Uncooperative termination | `PlatformNotSupportedException` — **hard crash** |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Cancellable work loop | Not cancellation-aware; can't be woken by a token |

## Additional Bugs in the Original

1. **Lost signals** — `WaitOne()` → `Reset()` race: a second `Enqueue` between them loses the `Set`, leaving items stuck.
2. **Single dequeue per wake** — Multiple enqueues produce one signal, but only one item is dequeued per loop iteration.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

The idiomatic replacement uses `Channel<T>`, which eliminates the manual lock, event, and thread management:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Clean shutdown — don't propagate.
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();       // Signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // Timeout fallback

        if (_runTask is not null)
            await _runTask;
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### If you need a synchronous `Stop()` (e.g., legacy callers)

```csharp
public void Stop()
{
    _channel.Writer.Complete();
    _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    _runTask?.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue<T>` | `Channel<string>` | Thread-safe producer/consumer with built-in signaling; fixes the lost-signal race |
| `new Thread(RunLoop)` | `Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(...))` | Uses the thread pool; `async` enables cancellation-aware waiting |
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | `_channel.Writer.Complete()` | Signals the reader to drain and exit gracefully |
| `_thread.Abort()` | `_cts.CancelAfter(5s)` | Cooperative timeout — `ReadAllAsync` checks the token and throws `OperationCanceledException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | The modern equivalent; filtered with `when` to avoid swallowing unrelated cancellations |

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **`Thread.Abort` throws at runtime** | It compiles on .NET 8 (with `SYSLIB0006` warning) but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. This is not a build error — it's a **runtime bomb**. |
| **`CancelAfter` isn't instant** | `Handle(item)` won't be interrupted mid-execution. If `Handle` is long-running, pass the token into it and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. |
| **Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It leaks timers internally (especially with `CancelAfter`). Implement `IDisposable`. |
| **`Channel.Writer.Complete()` lets drain finish** | Unlike `Abort`, this gracefully processes remaining items. Use `_cts.Cancel()` *immediately* instead of `CancelAfter` if you want to skip remaining items. |
